after Hamas is over? [Ilan] The only way is with two
states. [JG] It’s also a journey into his own past.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Into his own beliefs. How much of this remains after
7 October? [Itai] We think the solution is peace.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:19.000
[Rahel] It’s not enough to just want peace.
[JG] Meron Mendel wants to know: “What’s next for 

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
my Israel?”

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:45.000
[INTRO]

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:53.000
A suitcase full of pain. Returning to Israel is a
familiar feeling for Meron Mendel. But this time 

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.000
everything is different. Not all of his loved
ones survived the terrorist attack on 7 October.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
[MM] I’ve been living in Germany for over 20 years.
But all those years meant nothing in that moment. 

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:13.000
I suddenly realised that I belong there. That’s
where I grew up. That’s where my childhood friends

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:20.000
are. My family is there. I need to be there.
[JG] Meron Mendel came to Frankfurt in 2003.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Today he directs the Anne Frank Educational Centre
and is a professor of social work. The 47-year-old

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:31.000
is married to the political scientist
Saba-Nur Cheema. She’s a Muslim. He’s a Jew.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Together they promote diversity in society.
They’re passionate about peace in the Middle East. 

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Even now. What’s next for Israel? A very personal
question for Meron Mendel. And one he needs to 

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:55.000
ask to overcome his own trauma from 7 October.
He’ll get answers. And we’ll join him on his journey. 

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:05.000
[MM] I’ve been waiting for this moment for over a
month. Yes, I’m excited. But I’m also very tense.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:13.000
[Aeroplane announcement] “Solidarity with Israel”.
We arrive. The airport corridors are lined with 

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:25.000
pictures of hostages. As we’re about to leave…
We hear an air-raid siren. The next bunker is too

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:35.000
far away. The way there is too dangerous.
[MM] Now we’ve truly arrived. [JG] After a while,

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:44.000
we’re given the all-clear. We’re finally on the
way to Mashabe Sade. On the way home. But then…

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Our car breaks down in the middle of the highway.
It’s not long before a young Arab comes over. 

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:58.000
The Bedouin lives nearby and wants to help out as
fast as he can. A few minutes later, a Jewish-Israeli

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
reservist also stops to lend a hand. A fitting start to
our journey between cultures. Togetherness in action.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:13.000
This is the Israel that Meron Mendel 
knows and loves.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:23.000
[MM] Straight on. Straight on. We’re almost there.
[JG] First stop: his parents’ house. He hugs his

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:32.000
mother and father. That’s important to him. They’re
reunited after a year. Reunited after 7 October.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:40.000
[MM] What’s new in the kibbutz? [DM] Not much…
Well, there’s a war going on. That dictates  

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:49.000
everyday life. [MM] Have a lot of people from the
kibbutz been mobilised? [DM] Of course. There’s a

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:56.000
general mobilisation. All reservists have been
called up to the army. [JG] Fight for your own 

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:03.000
existence. That’s how Meron was raised. His parents
met during the Yom Kippur War in October 1973. 

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Many stories in Israel – even love stories – begin
with a battle. [DM] My father was in the War of

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Independence and the Six-Day War. I was in the 
Yom Kippur War. You were in the Lebanon War. And

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Eyal is in the Gaza War. [JG] Meron’s mother is
worried. For Israel and her sons. The youngest is

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:43.000
on the front line. [Haviva Mendel] Two, three, four 
soldiers are killed every day. I’m very worried.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:51.000
This is the kibbutz where Meron Mendel grew up. 
In the middle of the Negev Desert. [MM] Trees, meadows…

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Our kibbutz wanted to let the desert flourish. And
those hills are military training areas. I used to run

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:09.000
and shoot there back in the day. [JG] There are no
shooting drills at the moment. Most of the soldiers

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:16.000
are probably on duty in Gaza. Show respect. Work hard.
Share instead of owning. These values had a strong 

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:24.000
influence on his upbringing. [MM] And here’s the
school. [The sound of fighter jets] That’s 

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:32.000
completely normal: war up there, lessons down here.
[JG] One thing is much more exciting than war:

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:41.000
our camera. Meron was a pupil here himself 40
years ago. [MM] Is anyone here from near Gaza?

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:50.000
[Children] Me… me… me… [JG] The gate remains locked.
There are soldiers everywhere. They want to protect

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:58.000
themselves. From terrorists. [JG] What values were 
taught to you here as a child? What kind of person 

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:05.000
are you raised to be here in the kibbutz? [MM] The most
important thing is to be productive and 

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:16.000
contribute to the community. The entire kibbutz movement
is part of the peace movement. Hardly anyone supports

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:26.000
Netanyahu’s nationalist government. But that doesn’t
mean that you grow up together with Palestinians.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:32.000
[JG] Be open to other cultures. Live in peace with
everyone. But keep your distance. This attitude still

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:37.000
rings true in the kibbutz. Meron’s father has been
painting for many years. The 71-year-old deals 

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:44.000
with the problems facing the Bedouins. Around
200,000 of them live in Israel. Little attention

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:52.000
is paid to the nomadic Arab people. [DM] You 
wouldn’t believe it. There are high-voltage power

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:00.000
lines running over their huts, which are all made
of sheet metal. [JG] That particular metal hut is

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:08.000
home to Eid Ratil. Meron’s father visits him
regularly. The two often meet over a cup of tea.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:16.000
But it’s a friendship with limits. And those limits
were taught to Meron Mendel. You can play with local

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:23.000
Arab children. But you can’t welcome them into the
kibbutz. One reason: Kibbutzim are largely homogenous

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:30.000
communities. To this day. Meron Mendel has challenged
this idea more and more over the years. And he’s 

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:46.000
built up a circle of friends who advocate for peace
and cohesion between Jewish and Arab Israelis.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:52.000
One of them is Avital Benshalom. They’ve been 
close friends for many years. She stands here 

00:08:53.000 --> 00:09:00.000
every day, demanding the release of all hostages.
The same wish in every Israeli’s heart.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:10.000
[Avital Benshalom] These are the two cute redheads…
from Be’eri… It’s just awful… I haven’t even got

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:24.000
round to crying yet. [JG] A shoulder to cry on.
An important moment for Meron. [AB] I’m quite angry.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:34.000
Releasing the people isn’t the first goal of this
war. But it should be. [JG] One of the demonstrators

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
is Shaul Levy. He’s a family friend who has known Meron 
since he was little. His 19-year-old granddaughter,

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:48.000
Na’ama, was abducted. The footage has been seen
around the world. But instead of being comforted, 

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:56.000
he’s the comforter. [SL] Stay strong… [MM] I can’t.
I can’t get the images of Na’ama out of my head.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:08.000
I don’t know how you do it… [SL] You take a
deep breath… And keep going. There’s no other way.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:15.000
The young soldier had just started her military
service. Na’ama wanted to become a diplomat. 

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:29.000
She campaigned for reconciliation. [SL] She’s attended
lots of “Hands of Peace” forums abroad. Where Jews

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:37.000
meet Palestinians. [JG] Her chances of ever being
released are uncertain. Her grandfather still

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:45.000
believes in a happy ending. For Na’ama and the whole
of Israel. [SL] There’s hope… It’s not just hope.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:57.000
I’m sure we’ll get back on the right path. 
[JG] Meron is amazed by his strength. Hope and

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:04.000
grief are inextricably bound in this country.
Meron Mendel’s homeland is hurting. But it won’t 

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:13.000
give up just yet. [MM] I’m a bit more optimistic
than I was a few days ago. I see that people are

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:23.000
determined no matter what. As Avital and Shaul said,
we might be on the canvas right now, but now we can

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:32.000
rebuild. Make a fresh start. We have to rethink our
future and do something about it. I find that so 

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:43.000
strong. [JG] This optimism is 
constantly being put to the test.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:49.000
Rethinking the future is also inevitable for the
country’s many refugees. One of them is Itai. 

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.000
A friend from Meron’s university days. 
His German-Israeli family lived in a town on the

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:02.000
border with Gaza. Until two months ago. They want to
go back. They want to know how things are at home.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.000
[MM] You can probably remember a few years back…
We were hiking through the desert with a few friends

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:14.000
of mine from Germany, with sleeping bags and
everything. My friends asked you what it was like

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:21.000
living on the border with Gaza. And you said so
casually: It’s not a problem with all the rockets

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.000
because we live so close to the border. They fly
over us to Ashkelon, to Tel Aviv. It’s safe where

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:33.000
we are. [JG] Safety: a feeling that has been gone
since 7 October. Meron tried to reach his friend

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.000
for hours. It wasn’t until late in the evening that
that he knew they were alive. [MM] That was one of

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:49.000
the nicest messages I’ve ever received.
[JG] The place almost seems dead. When the siren

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:55.000
sounds, you have 15 seconds to get to safety.
There are shelters everywhere. Many of them served

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:03.000
as a refuge on 7 October. [Itai] An old woman,
the mother of a close childhood friend. She ran from

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:13.000
her house behind that tree into there. A terrorist
saw her inside and shot her. [JG] Itai lost 20 

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:21.000
neighbours that day. Those who lived here are either
dead or have fled. They were torn from their lives.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:29.000
All that’s left here are a few abandoned cats. 
Explosions are still ringing out. The Gaza Strip

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:37.000
is just a few hundred metres away. [MM] I spent a
lot of time in Gaza as a child. Not in that part but 

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:45.000
on the beach. It was the closest beach to the kibbutz.
We played with Palestinian children in the sand.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:52.000
Things were much different back then. [JG] Despite all
the destruction, as soon as Itai turns onto his street, 

00:13:53.000 --> 00:14:14.000
he feels at home. [Itai] That’s our house. Home at
last… And here… This is our shelter. This is where 

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:24.000
we were on 7 October. There was a mattress here.
I took things from the fridge. [JG] They spent 

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:29.000
over 12 hours here in the dark. Itai and his
daughter came up with an emergency plan. They hid 

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:35.000
two long kitchen knives in the cupboard.
[Maya Shimonovich] If someone were to come in,

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:43.000
I was going to hide in here and the they would have
the knives. [MM] Were you scared? [MS] Yes, very.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:51.000
They take some food and their favourite clothes.
At least a little bit of their normal lives.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:58.000
Will they ever be able to live here again? Itai
wants to come back. However: [Itai] I hope that it’s

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:05.000
actually safe to come back. We’re peaceful people. 
We think the solution is peace.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:12.000
[Tini Maisberger] We actually felt completely safe 
here before 7 October. We thought we were living in 

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:24.000
maximum security. We never locked the house. We left
the car key in the ignition at times. And the children 

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:37.000
were out at night with friends in the village. We 
thought everything was completely safe. But it turns

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:44.000
out it’s not. It’s not safe at all. [JG] You can sense
the inner conflict. This is their home. Or at least

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:55.000
it was. They’re currently staying with relatives,
about a 4-hour drive from Netiv HaAsara. There we 

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:01.000
meet Itai’s wife Tini and daughter Maya again.
Tini is from Munich. She was in Germany on 7 October.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:09.000
She found out about the terrorist attack via
WhatsApp. [TM] It’s obviously awful when you’re 

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:18.000
3,000 km away and can’t do anything. [JG] It was
an agonising wait, not knowing whether she would 

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:27.000
ever see her family again. But Tini doesn’t feel hate.
She feels sympathy – for the people in Gaza.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:34.000
[TM] I can’t change the way things are. But I just
think it’s an important feeling to have. You shouldn’t

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:42.000
just close yourself off and have no compassion.
[JG] Maya is defying Hamas’s terror with unwavering

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:53.000
hope. She sees her future in Israel. [MS] I love
Israel! Perhaps my dreams are too big, but I just 

00:16:54.000 --> 00:17:02.000
want peace. Because there was a lot of hate here 
before the war. Not only between Palestinians and

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:18.000
Israelis, but also amongst people in Israel.
I just want us to love and see one another.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:25.000
[JG] She refuses to let 7 October divide her family,
destroy her values or shake her belief in a peaceful

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:37.000
Israel. [JG] Not all of Meron’s friends survived.
Shachar and her husband Shlomi were brutally murdered.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:43.000
Shachar’s family is like a second home to Meron. 
He’s been friends with her brother Yehuda since 

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:51.000
they were 15. Her parents see Meron as their own
son. [Ilan] Welcome. How are you? [JG] Asks a man

00:17:52.000 --> 00:18:23.000
in need of comfort himself. For her mother, 
Rahel, there’s nothing left to say.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:31.000
[Rahel Troen] At the funeral, I found myself
repeating the words of a song: 'Sometimes it’s me,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Sometimes it’s you, Who is so in need of comfort'.
I felt it was important to comfort one another.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:19:00.000
[JG] It’s a song that Shachar used 
to sing herself.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:08.000
Shachar. Her name meant “sunrise”. She was known
her gentle heart, confident of peace. Her family

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:22.000
can’t fathom her death. [IT] Our children believed in
the possibilities of mutual understanding. Not just

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:29.000
of stereotyping and hating one another.
[RT] They believed it was important to engage with 

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:37.000
people who are actually different, who have different
beliefs. Not only a different language, a different

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:43.000
culture. [JG] Shachar and her husband Shlomi made
a conscious decision to move to Kibbutz Holit.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:48.000
Knowing full well that living near Gaza could be 
dangerous. They refused to be intimidated. 

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:57.000
They wanted to have a positive impact on society.
They co-founded a Jewish-Arab school.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:06.000
[Yehuda Troen] There was a special happiness that 
she had. I’ll miss it. [JG] They’d celebrated her

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:13.000
50th birthday just 6 days before her death. Full of
laughter, warmth and friendliness. That’s how

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:21.000
Shachar was. And so was the Israel she died for.
[YT] She was so happy. Shlomi was so happy.  They were

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:35.000
so good together. That’s how I’ll try to 
remember her. And not focus on her horrible death.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:42.000
Her father Ilan is looking for a rational explanation
to cope with the loss. His view: Hamas wanted to

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:54.000
exterminate the Jews. [MM] Has your political opinion
changed since 7 October? [IT] For me it’s become 

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:01.000
even more stuck. It made me even more convinced
that the only way is with two states. For me it’s

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:11.000
proof that it’s impossible for one people to take
this whole territory. So maybe this could be a 

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:17.000
turning point. Maybe. [JG] Could 7 October really
be a turning point? They’d like to think so.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:25.000
But Rahel also admits that it’s never been as hard 
to cling on to peace as it is now. [RT] It’s not enough

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:31.000
to just want peace and work for peace, coexistence 
and mutual understanding. If you’re working with

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:39.000
somebody who actually rejects the very idea of it.
[JG] Meron would like to pay his respects at her grave.
