00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:43.000
Our destination: Hebron. A microcosm of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict. Nowhere are settlers 

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:51.000
and Palestinians confronted so directly. Meron Mendel
spent a lot of time there as a young soldier.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:59.000
What does the region look like today, especially
after 7 October? [JG] What is your most vivid

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:09.000
memory of Hebron? [MM] The settlers in Hebron who
threw stones at passers-by from the rooftops.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:17.000
An extreme racist ideology is drilled into them
from the start. They think they’re better than

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:24.000
the rest. [JG] In 1997, the city was divided into
a Palestinian and a Jewish sector. The latter is

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:29.000
controlled by the Israeli military. The market is
in the heart of the Palestinian sector. Each seller 

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:34.000
tries to outprice the other on vegetables. It seems
bizarrely normal. But Meron also notices that

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:44.000
the city has changed. And not for the better.
This road used to be open. [MM] Here we can already

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:50.000
see the first settlements in Hebron. [JG] So now
we’re in Palestinian territory. [MM] That’s right.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:57.000
[JG] And that’s Israeli territory over there. 
[MM] Yes and no. That settlement is Jewish, 

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:05.000
so to speak, but the house next door is Palestinian.
So they’re really just individual houses along

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:17.000
that street. [JG] We’re not allowed on the Jewish
side. The soldiers send us to the next checkpoint. 

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:27.000
[MM] She asked whether we were Jewish. [JG] To get in?
[M] Yes, to get in. I’m shocked. [JG] They check 

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:34.000
our passports and press badges. No luck. That’s
the end of the road for today. [MM] Thousands of

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:43.000
Palestinians live there. And now they’re almost 
imprisoned. I don’t know how they get to their houses.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:48.000
Or have they already been kicked out? [JG] We soon
get an answer. This Palestinian lives in the 

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:59.000
Jewish sector. [Ismael Kakarki] They only open the
gate on Sundays, Tuesdays and Thursdays. From 7 am

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:07.000
to 5 pm. [JG] He says that access regulations have
been even stricter since 7 October. The residents

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:14.000
are harassed on a daily basis. [IK] Our life is a
tragedy. We’re living in one big prison We’re not

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:18.000
allowed to open our windows. Women are assaulted. 
And we use the roofs to hang out our laundry. 

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:24.000
Today is Saturday. The settlers will drink
alcohol and throw bottles at our windows.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:30.000
[JG] At the time Hebron was divided, around 35,000
Palestinians were living in the Jewish sector. Just ten 

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:40.000
years later, over 40% of them had left the area.
[MM] Those Jewish settlers have no place in this

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:51.000
city. More generally speaking, there should
be no settlements anywhere in the West Bank.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:57.000
The only solution to this conflict is the 
two-state solution. [JG] Hebron is an extreme case.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:04.000
Peaceful coexistence seems impossible there.
But there are also places in Israel where Jews and 

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:09.000
Palestinians can interact without restrictions.
Those approaches need to be promoted even more,

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:18.000
says Meron Mendel. 
Like these boys and girls. True beacons of hope

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:24.000
for Meron Mendel. This is the only bilingual school 
in southern Israel. A project that is particularly

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:33.000
close to the educator’s heart. Here he meets 
Avital again. She runs the school. [AB] So this is

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:42.000
our school. We have a vision to create an equal
educational environment for Jewish and Arab 

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:49.000
students. [JG] Over 300 children learn side by side
here up to the 6th grade. It’s been this way for

00:32:50.000 --> 00:33:02.000
15 years. Even now, in times of war. They’ve set up
a little mourning corner. [AB] To show their compassion

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:11.000
towards everyone: soldiers, their families here in 
